[1] Update
Date: Wed 18 Sep 2013
Source: Calgary Herald [edited]
http://www.calgaryherald.com/health/Health+officials+issue+alert+tainted+cheese+after+death+fall/8928719/story.html


Federal and provincial health officials are warning Albertans to avoid eating some raw milk cheeses in the wake of a bacterial outbreak in which one patient has died and as many as 16 others have fallen ill. Consumers in British Columbia [BC] and Alberta began getting sick in late July 2013 after eating product from Gort's Gouda Cheese Farm, but it wasn't until late last week [week of 9 Sep 2013] that provincial epidemiologists linked the growing cluster of _E. coli_ O157: H7 cases to the Salmon Arm manufacturer and notified the Canadian Food Inspection Agency [CFIA].

CFIA officials issued a health alert late Tue 17 Sep 2013, for all cheeses sold at the company's farm outlet, at retail stores in the 2 provinces and through the Internet from 27 May 2013 to 14 Sep 2013. Lot codes 122 through 138 are affected by the recall.

Dr James Talbot, Alberta's chief medical officer of health, said 7 people who fell sick in the province, 5 from Calgary and 2 from Edmonton, have been genetically linked to the tainted cheese and another 2 incidents of illness are under investigation because their food history indicates the patients may have eaten the company's product. 2 of the confirmed cases became sick in late July 2013, but the remaining 5 fell ill between the last week of August 2013 and the 1st few days of September 2013.

Talbot said the patients' food histories tipped off investigators. "Most of the cases had travelled to BC and purchased product from the farm, so that's a pretty unusual pattern," he said.

None of the Albertans who have fallen ill have had to be hospitalized, but among the 8 confirmed or suspected cases in BC is a patient from that province's Interior region who died in August 2013.

On Wed 18 Sep 2013, federal food inspectors were again at the facility preparing an inventory of potentially contaminated products on site that will need to be destroyed, and those in the market that will need to be recalled. "The affected products were sold at the manufacturer's outlet (35 percent of total sales), at retail stores primarily in British Columbia, as well as some stores in Alberta," CFIA spokesman Guy Gravelle said in an email reply to questions. "In addition, there are mail order and online sales, mainly in Western Canada."

[Byline: Matt McClure]

