[2] Bovine vaccination
Date: Wed 18 Sep 2013
Source: MedPage Today [edited]
http://www.medpagetoday.com/InfectiousDisease/Vaccines/41704


Widespread vaccination of cattle against _Escherichia coli_ O157 could vastly decrease the human incidence of disease associated with this pathogen, a mathematical simulation suggested.

If the effects of the vaccine simply reflected its efficacy in cattle, a 50 percent reduction in cases would be expected because the vaccine has been shown to halve the fecal shedding of the pathogen, according to Louise Matthews, PhD, of the University of Glasgow, and colleagues. However, because the vaccine targets high-density shedding strains of _E. coli_ O157, so-called supershedders, the decrease in human cases could be expected to reach 83 percent (95 percent CI [confidence interval] 76-93), the researchers reported online in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences.

Vaccines have been developed, but considerable obstacles to their use exist. In Canada, one vaccine has been licensed, but in the USA only partial licensure has been granted to the 2 available vaccines. "There are conflicting responsibilities of the medical and veterinary agencies. The bodies charged with licensing vaccines in animals must typically certify that controls are not just safe but improve animal health; this remit poses a problem for the control of zoonotic pathogens that are benign in their reservoir," Matthews and colleagues explained.

Data on the scope of effects of cattle vaccination on human disease would be essential for such a system to be developed, so the researchers calculated mathematical models that take into account the inevitable heterogeneity of transmission between species. They noted that specific genetic markers that relate to the pathogens' ability to produce Shiga toxin (stx2 and stx2c) have been linked with human disease, but the epidemiology of these strains in the cattle host and effects on shedding intensity has been unclear.

Supershedding has received considerable attention as a factor in infectious transmission between cattle, but hasn't been considered in relation to cross-species transmission. The researchers analyzed data from Health Protection Scotland, identifying 237 human cases that occurred between 2002 and 2004, and tested almost 13 000 cattle fecal samples, finding 4 percent that were positive for _E. coli_ O157. They had previously reported that the most common phage types (PTs) of the pathogen found in cattle in Scotland were PT 21/28, which is a supershedding strain, while PT 32 is a non-supershedding strain.

When they analyzed the frequency of PT 21/28 among samples from the human cases, they found it to be far more common than would be expected according to how frequently it's identified in cattle (P less than 0.001), while PT 32 is found less frequently (P less than 0.001). They then calculated that the most accurate model predicting the supershedding strains in the human cases involved a threshold shedding level of 1300 colony-forming units per gram (cfu/g) of feces (95 percent CI 600-2300).

Further analysis determined that the stx2 variant is found much more frequently in the supershedding strain, and that high concentrations of shedding in this variant had an odds ratio of 6.54 for the threshold level of 1300 cfu/g to be met (P less than 0.001). This finding confirmed that high shedding is the predominant factor influencing human disease, rather than features such as differences in clinical pathogenicity once transmission has occurred.

This threshold of 1300 cfu/g was then used to determine that eliminating only the 12 percent of highest shedding densities through vaccination would result in the 50 percent reduction in cattle and 83 percent decline in human cases.

"Because the currently available vaccines reduce high-concentration shedding of the pathogen by cattle, which we show to heavily influence transmission across the species boundary, they should be especially effective at reducing the number of human illnesses," Matthews and colleagues predicted.

Thus far, Canada is the only country to grant a full license to the vaccine. "Uptake, however, is poor, with the vaccine reaching less than 5 percent of the market, a likely consequence of the fact that, currently farmers would bear the cost of vaccination but receive no direct perceived benefit, because the cattle harbor the organism without succumbing to clinical disease," the researchers noted.

"A coordinated approach would help close the current gap in remit between the separate agencies licensing human and veterinary interventions and provide a starting point for assessing how the costs of interventions might be borne across the multiple stakeholders," they concluded.

[Byline: Nancy Walsh]

