[The citation for the Mathews paper, in press, is Matthews L, Reeve R, Gally DL, et al: Predicting the public health benefit of vaccinating cattle against _Escherichia coli_ O157. Proc Natl Acad Sci USA 2013 http://www.pnas.org/cgi/doi/10.1073/pnas.1304978110.

Regarding supershedders and EHEC vaccines, the following is extracted from Lutwick LI: Enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_ infections. In: Confronting Emerging Zoonoses: The One Health Paradigm. Yamada A, Kahn LH, Kaplan B, Monath TP, Woodall J, Conti LA (eds) Springer, Tokyo, Japan, (in press) with the citations removed:

Most infected cattle pass EHEC in stool at low numbers (less than 100 colony forming units/gram stool). Such low numbers can make detection difficult, often underestimating overall carriage prevalence and excretion is often intermittent. Some animals, however, harbor quite high amounts of EHEC for prolonged amounts of time. One report found that 9 percent of carriers excreted over 96 percent of total EHEC. It is these animals, termed supershedders, which are the major transmitters to other animals' gastrointestinal tracts and/or hides. Non-EHEC shedding cattle are 5 times more likely not to be housed with a supershedder. Supershedding is linked to colonization of the rectoanal junction of the animal where proteins other than LEE [locus of enterocyte effacement] seem to contribute to adherence to the rectoanal junction stratified squamous epithelial cells.

....a serotype O157 outer membrane-based vaccine (siderophore receptor and porin proteins) reduced the overall prevalence of _E. coli_ O157:H7 as well as the prevalence of supershedders. This large study confirmed the observations of older, smaller studies. A meta-analysis of this vaccine and a second commercial vaccine targeting the type III secretion system proteins also suggested bovine vaccination as an effective modality in the control of EHEC in humans. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/3han.]
